<BlogPostLayout
  title="Building a Custom Interactive Star Rating Widget in Flutter"
  description="A step-by-step guide to building a fully interactive, gesture-driven star rating widget from scratch — no packages required."
  canonicalUrl="https://waseemarain4u.github.io/my-portfolio/blog-article-star-rating"
  ogImage="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1618477388954-7852f32655ec?w=1200&q=80"
  tag="Flutter"
  date="Aug 12, 2023"
  readTime="5 min read"
  mediumUrl="https://medium.com/@waseemarain_98671/building-a-custom-interactive-star-rating-widget-in-flutter-31c7ed9fb261"
>
  <p>Flutter's widget ecosystem is rich, but there are moments where building from scratch teaches you far more than dropping in a package. The star rating widget is a perfect exercise — it involves custom painting, gesture detection, and state management all in one compact component.</p>

  <h2>Why build it yourself?</h2>
  <p>There are plenty of star rating packages on pub.dev. But building your own gives you complete control over the visual design, interaction behaviour, half-star support, animation, and accessibility. More importantly, it forces you to understand Flutter's gesture system and custom painting pipeline — knowledge that pays dividends across many other custom widgets.</p>

  <h2>The core approach: GestureDetector + CustomPaint</h2>
  <p>The widget is built around two Flutter primitives. <code>GestureDetector</code> captures horizontal drag gestures to update the rating in real-time as the user drags across the stars. <code>CustomPaint</code> draws the stars precisely, filling them based on the current value.</p>
  <pre>class StarRating extends StatefulWidget {'{'}
  final double initialRating;
  final int starCount;
  final ValueChanged&lt;double&gt; onRatingChanged;

  const StarRating({'{'}
    super.key,
    this.initialRating = 0,
    this.starCount = 5,
    required this.onRatingChanged,
  {'}'});
{'}'}</pre>
  <p>Keeping the widget stateful internally while exposing the value through a callback keeps the API clean — the parent decides what to do with the rating, and the widget manages its own visual state.</p>

  <h2>Handling gestures for a smooth experience</h2>
  <p>The key to a satisfying drag interaction is converting the horizontal position of the user's finger into a rating value. You calculate the rating by dividing the drag offset by the total widget width, then clamping it between 0 and the maximum star count. Rounding to the nearest 0.5 gives you half-star precision.</p>
  <pre>double _calculateRating(double localX, double totalWidth) {'{'}
  final raw = (localX / totalWidth) * widget.starCount;
  // Round to nearest half
  return (raw * 2).round() / 2.0.clamp(0, widget.starCount.toDouble());
{'}'}</pre>
  <p>Wiring this to both <code>onHorizontalDragUpdate</code> and <code>onTapDown</code> means the widget responds correctly to both taps and drags.</p>

  <h2>Drawing the stars with CustomPainter</h2>
  <p>The <code>StarPainter</code> class uses a <code>Path</code> to trace a five-pointed star polygon for each position. For filled stars it uses the accent colour; for empty stars it uses a muted stroke. For partially filled stars — the half-star case — it uses a <code>clipRect</code> to paint the filled version up to the fractional point, then the empty version for the remainder.</p>
  <p>The result is a smooth, pixel-perfect rating widget that matches your app's design language exactly, responds to gestures naturally, and works on every Flutter platform without any external dependency.</p>

  <h2>Adding animation</h2>
  <p>Wrapping each star's scale in an <code>AnimationController</code> driven by the current rating adds a satisfying pop when a star becomes selected. Keep it subtle — a scale from 1.0 to 1.2 and back over 150ms is enough to feel responsive without being distracting.</p>
  <p>The full implementation is available on Medium with complete source code. The entire widget comes in under 150 lines of Dart.</p>

